\begin_inset Formula $\text{span}\{\mathbf{w}_{1},\mathbf{w}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{w}_{j}\}=\text{span}\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{j}=\text{span}\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

, making 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{j}$
\end_inset

 a vector space with dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is by construction a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 and therefore in 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{1}=\text{span}\{\mathbf{b}_{1}\}\subset W_{2}=\text{span}\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2}\}\subset\cdots\subset W_{j}=\text{span}\{\mathbf{b}_{1},\mathbf{b}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{b}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{1},\mathbf{w}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{w}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are all in 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 If we knew that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{1},\mathbf{w}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{w}_{j}$
\end_inset

 were linearly independent, we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

